[$k$-metric antidimension and $k$-antiresolving basis]\label{def_metric_antidimension}
The $k$-\emph{metric antidimension} of a simple connected graph $G = (V, E)$ is the
minimum cardinality amongst the $k$-antiresolving sets in $G$ and is denoted by $\adim_k(G)$. A $k$-antiresolving set of cardinality $\adim_k(G)$ is called a $k$-\emph{antiresolving basis} for $G$.

A finite set of integers $A$ is a $2t+2$-\emph{compact set} if and only if the following conditions hold:
\begin{itemize}
\item[(i)] $-1,-2, \ldots, -2t-1$ belong to $A$;
\item[(ii)] for all $a \in A$ such that $a \neq -1,-2, \ldots, -2t-1$, we have $a \geq 1$ and $a \not\equiv 0~\mbox{mod~} 2t+2$;
\item[(iii)] let $b>a \geq 1$ be two integers such that $a \equiv b$ mod $2t+2$. If $b \in A$, then $a \in A$.
\end{itemize}

