\label{df:dp}
Fix $n\in\N$ and $\e\ge0$. The $\e$-differential privacy polytope, $\D\subset\R^{n\times n}$, is defined as follows:
\begin{align}\label{eq:sm}
\D=\left\{A\in\R^{n\times n}:\begin{array}{ll}\sum_j a_{ij}=1, & \forall\;1\le i\le n,\\
a_{ij}\ge 0, & \forall\;1\le i,j\le n,\\
a_{ij}\le e^\e a_{kj}, & \forall\;1\le i,j,k\le n.\end{array}\right\}.
\end{align}

%$\D$ consists of non-negative, stochastic matrices, with entries in the same column separated by a maximum multiplicative factor of $e^\e$.
The non-negativity and stochastic constraints ensure $\D$ is bounded. Therefore it is a polytope.

